---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'SaaS &amp; web application development';
const description =
  'Custom dashboards, B2B tools, internal portals, and full SaaS products. Apriori Studio builds web applications with authentication, billing, integrations, and a deploy pipeline you can trust.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="SaaS and web application development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/web', label: 'Websites' },
    { href: '/web/saas', label: 'SaaS &amp; web apps' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Web applications are different from marketing sites in almost every way that matters.
    Marketing sites are read mostly once, cached aggressively, and serve millions if needed.
    Web apps are read and written constantly by a smaller group of users who care about every
    detail of how the thing behaves at three in the morning when something breaks. Building one
    well takes a different mindset, different tools, and a different kind of attention to
    long-term maintenance. We have all three.
  </p>

  <h2>What counts as a web app</h2>
  <p>
    The line is fuzzy, but if your project includes any of the following, it's an app, not a
    site: user accounts, recurring billing, role-based permissions, multi-tenant data, real-time
    updates, complex forms, integrations with external APIs that need authentication, document
    or file processing, scheduled background jobs, an admin panel, or anything you'd describe as
    "the dashboard." Examples we've worked on: B2B dashboards for ops teams, internal tools that
    replaced a spreadsheet that grew out of control, customer portals, project management apps
    for a specific niche, marketplace platforms.
  </p>

  <h2>Tech stack we use</h2>
  <p>
    For most apps we work in <strong>Next.js</strong> or <strong>React</strong> on the
    frontend, with <strong>Laravel</strong>, <strong>Node.js</strong>, or
    <strong>FastAPI</strong> on the backend depending on what you and your team will be most
    comfortable maintaining. Database is usually <strong>PostgreSQL</strong> or
    <strong>MySQL</strong>. Background jobs run on <strong>Redis</strong>-backed queues.
    Real-time features use WebSockets. Hosting goes on a proper VPS or managed Kubernetes
    depending on scale, with Cloudflare in front for caching and DDoS protection.
  </p>
  <p>
    We don't chase trends. We pick boring, well-documented tools that you'll be able to hire
    for and that will still be supported in five years. If you have an existing team or
    preferred stack, we'll adapt — we've worked across most of the popular Web frameworks.
  </p>

  <h2>Engineering practices</h2>

  <h3>Authentication and access control</h3>
  <p>
    Email + password with proper hashing (Argon2id), email verification, password reset, and
    optional two-factor (TOTP via Authenticator app, or WebAuthn for passwordless). Single
    sign-on (Google, Microsoft, GitHub) where it fits. Role-based access control with policies
    you can audit. Session handling that survives a server restart. Rate-limiting on
    authentication endpoints to stop credential-stuffing attacks before they start.
  </p>

  <h3>Billing and subscriptions</h3>
  <p>
    Stripe Billing for most cases — recurring subscriptions, metered usage, prorated upgrades,
    failed-payment dunning, invoicing, tax via Stripe Tax. We integrate the webhooks properly
    so your app knows immediately when a customer cancels or fails a payment, not at the next
    cron run. For UK and EU VAT compliance we set up MOSS / OSS handling correctly.
  </p>

  <h3>Multi-tenancy and data isolation</h3>
  <p>
    If your app serves multiple customers (organisations, teams, workspaces), we structure the
    database so one tenant can't accidentally see another's data — using row-level security,
    schema-per-tenant, or database-per-tenant depending on the scale and isolation requirements.
    We add the right indexes and audit logs from the start, not after a security review goes
    sideways.
  </p>

  <h3>Deployment, monitoring and backups</h3>
  <p>
    Continuous deployment from your Git repository. Zero-downtime releases. Database migrations
    that run safely. Application monitoring (Sentry for errors, a metrics dashboard for what
    matters to your business), uptime checks with alerts to a real human. Daily off-site backups
    of the database, with periodic restore tests so you know they actually work.
  </p>

  <h3>Security and compliance</h3>
  <p>
    HTTPS-only with HSTS, CSRF and XSS protection at the framework level, parameterised
    queries everywhere, secrets in environment variables (never in code), regular dependency
    updates with security patches, password policies that follow current NIST guidance (length
    over arbitrary complexity rules). For regulated industries we can implement audit logs,
    data residency controls, and the documentation needed for SOC 2 or ISO 27001 prep.
  </p>

  <h3>API and integrations</h3>
  <p>
    REST or GraphQL — both fine, both have trade-offs, we'll pick the one that fits your use
    case. OpenAPI documentation generated from the code, so it stays current. Webhooks out for
    your customers to integrate with. OAuth 2.0 server if you need third-party developers to
    build on top of your app.
  </p>

  <h2>How we approach a SaaS project</h2>
  <p>
    Web apps are higher-stakes builds than marketing sites, so we start with a discovery phase
    — usually one to two weeks of working sessions, technical research, and a written brief that
    captures what we're building, what we're explicitly not building, the data model, the user
    journeys, the third-party services involved, and the success metrics. That brief becomes
    the contract. Changes happen in writing.
  </p>
  <p>
    From there we ship a thin slice end-to-end first — usually authentication, one core page,
    one core action — so you can use it before we go deep on features. Every fortnight there's
    a working build on staging, and we course-correct based on what you actually use rather
    than what was speculated about in the brief.
  </p>

  <h2>Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    Web apps are quoted per-project after discovery — there's no honest single-line price.
    Discovery itself is fixed-price, usually £1,500 to £3,000 for a one-week sprint. A
    minimum-viable SaaS product (auth, billing, two or three core features, basic admin) starts
    around £20,000 and goes up depending on integrations and complexity. Internal tools that
    replace a spreadsheet typically come in at £8,000 to £18,000. We'll write all of this
    clearly in the proposal, and the proposal is free.
  </p>

  <h2>After launch</h2>
  <p>
    Web apps are never finished — they evolve as your business does. We offer ongoing
    development on a retainer (a fixed number of hours per month) or per-project for specific
    features. Either way, you have one developer who knows the codebase, not a different
    person every quarter. If you'd rather hire your own team and take it in-house, we'll hand
    over with documentation and pair-programming sessions to get them up to speed.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
